<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- TITLE -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Create Player Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        How to add the player start point, configure the player character, set the position, and choose the correct trigger settings.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- OVERVIEW -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What the Player Event Point Does
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The first Event Point added to a new mission is usually a <Bold>Player</Bold> Event Point.
        This event point defines the player character and the position where the player starts when
        the mission begins.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Without a valid Player Event Point, the mission may not start correctly in game. The player
        event point is therefore one of the most important setup entries in a new
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">.UCM</Run>
        mission file.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_player_eventpoint_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#3A2A2A" BorderBrush="#7A4A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0A0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Only place one Player Event Point for a normal single-player mission. If two Player Event Points are placed,
                    the game can treat the mission as a multiplayer-style level.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- ADD PLAYER EP -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Adding the Player Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To add the player start point, open the <Bold>Event Points</Bold> panel and click
        <Bold>Add</Bold>. In the <Bold>Add New EventPoint</Bold> window, select the
        <Bold>Player</Bold> Event Point type and click <Bold>OK</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_player_select_player_type.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph>
        The editor then opens the <Bold>Edit EventPoint</Bold> window. This window automatically
        adapts to the selected Event Point type. For a Player Event Point, it displays the common
        properties, position controls, player selection, trigger settings, and listening mode.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_player_edit_window.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Player Grouping and Position
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        For a Player Event Point, choose a letter and colour that you are unlikely to reuse for
        other mission logic. A practical example is <Bold>Black A</Bold>. This makes the player start
        point easy to distinguish from objective chains, enemy groups, item groups, and scripted
        mission logic.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Use <Bold>Select Position on Map</Bold> to place the player start in a clear, playable
        location. Enable map layers such as textures, buildings, and objects so the player is not
        accidentally placed inside geometry, behind a wall, or in an unsuitable area.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_player_common_properties.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_player_select_position_button.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_player_position_on_map.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>


    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- PLAYER TYPE -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Player Character
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Player-specific properties allow you to choose which character is used for the mission.
        Select the desired player radio button.
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Darci</Bold> — uses Darci as the player character.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Roper</Bold> — uses Roper as the player character.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Police Man</Bold> — uses the police officer player type.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Gang Member / Mako</Bold> — uses the gang member/Mako-style player type.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_player_character_selection.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- TRIGGER SETTINGS -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Recommended Trigger Settings for the Player
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Trigger settings define how and when an Event Point begins or becomes active. For the Player
        Event Point, the normal setup is simple:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Triggered By:</Bold> None / Game Starts.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Listening Mode:</Bold> Active.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        This means the Player Event Point is active as soon as the mission starts and remains active.
        For a standard mission, this is the expected setup.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_player_trigger_settings.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Typical Player setup:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Darci + Triggered By None/Game Starts + Listening Mode Active is a good basic test configuration.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- SAVE / VERIFY -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Saving the Player Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Once the common properties, position, player character, trigger, and listening mode are set,
        click <Bold>OK</Bold>. The Player Event Point is added to the Event Points list and appears
        in the viewport at the selected location.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_player_created_in_list.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- TESTING -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Testing the Player Start in Game
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        After adding the Player Event Point, save the mission file. For example, save it as:
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Border Background="#25272B" BorderBrush="#444" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="10">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0" FontFamily="Consolas">
test.ucm
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph>
        Save the file into the game’s levels folder. Then run the game with debug mode enabled and
        use the <Bold>Ctrl+R</Bold> debug loading method. Select <Bold>Load Level</Bold>, then select
        the saved
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">test.ucm</Run>
        file.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        If the Player Event Point, map file, and light file have been configured correctly, the game
        should load into the selected map with the chosen player character and selected light file.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Troubleshooting:</Run>
                <Run>
                    If the mission loads with the wrong map or wrong lighting, check Mission Properties and confirm
                    the map and light filenames were saved into the UCM file, not just loaded into the viewport.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- BASIC WORKFLOW -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Basic Player Event Point Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create or open a mission.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Load the map and light file for reference.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>Add</Bold> in the Event Points panel.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select <Bold>Player</Bold> and click <Bold>OK</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Choose a rarely reused colour and letter group, such as <Bold>Black A</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>Select Position on Map</Bold> and place the player start location.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select the player character, such as <Bold>Darci</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Triggered By</Bold> to <Bold>None / Game Starts</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Listening Mode</Bold> to <Bold>Active</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>OK</Bold> and save the mission.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test the mission in game using debug level loading.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

</FlowDocument>
